  "facts": [
    {
      "id": 1,
      "text": "Lakeville sits at the northern end of Conesus Lake, the westernmost Finger Lake, where the lake flows into Conesus Creek.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        6
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lakeville%2C_New_York"
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "text": "Route 20A cuts through Lakeville, linking it 2 miles east to Livonia village and 6 miles west to Geneseo.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        8
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lakeville%2C_New_York"
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "text": "In 1792 John Bosley built a mill on the lake outlet, sparking the first settlement in Lakeville.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        10
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://livonianyhistory.org/town-history/lakeville-conesus-lake/"
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "text": "During the late 1800s, excursion trains brought hundreds of visitors to Lakeville, where they boarded steamers like the MacPherson.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        11
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://livonianyhistory.org/town-history/lakeville-conesus-lake/"
    },
    {
      "id": 5,
      "text": "The Town of Livonia now owns over 6 acres of parkland on Lakeville’s north shore, once a bustling train unloading spot.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        13
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://livonianyhistory.org/town-history/lakeville-conesus-lake/"
    },
    {
      "id": 6,
      "text": "Lakeville was originally called “Ga‑ne‑a‑sos” by Native Americans, meaning “at the foot of the lake.”",
